stern Iranian airspace\n   - Non-weather (security/military) rationale\n\n5. **Timing:** The NOTAM was effective May 22, well before the May 24, 11:59 PM ET deadline.\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nThe central dispute is whether A1010/26 proves a \"major closure\" under the rule. The defense argues it's only an airport-operations restriction (QFALC = aerodrome closed), not an airspace/FIR closure. The plaintiff argues the practical effect - closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR with suspended permissions - qualifies as a major regional closure under the rule's plain language.\n\nThe rule does NOT require:\n- A national shutdown\n- A particular NOTAM code\n- A route closure\n- An airspace closure label\n\nThe rule DOES require: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region OR the airspace itself.\n\nThe NOTAM closed ALL airports in the western Tehran FIR (a major Iranian airspace region). The western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region. All airports being closed in that region means commercial flights cannot arrive, depart, or transit through those airports in that region. With all airports closed, there are no arrivals or departures in that region, satisfying the \"arriving in, and departing from\" portion.\n\nThe rule explicitly states \"Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\" The eight exception airports with daylight-only, CAA-approval required operations are the exact type of limited exceptions the rule expressly permits.\n\nThe NOTAM suspended all previous permissions for all operators, which is a broad suspension. While the Q-code is QFALC (aerodrome closed), the market rule is written in terms of commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy.\n\n**Weight of Evidence:**\n\nTheNOTAM is au