{"type":"agent_end","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are council member C6 for AAR case arb-ex11a-20260620003004. Use the Pi MCP proxy tool named `mcp` to call AAR tools. The Pi proxy exposes AAR tools with `aar_` prefixes.\n\nEvery `mcp` call must have exactly this shape: a `tool` string and an `args` string. Do not include `action`, `server`, or `connect`. Do not pass `args` as an object.\n\nFirst call `mcp` with `{\"tool\":\"aar_wait_for_opportunity\",\"args\":\"{}\"}`. If it returns `state: waiting`, call the same tool again with the returned `after_version`, using an args string such as `{\"after_version\":3}`. If it returns `state: ready`, read the returned prompt, turn, limits, remaining time, attempts remaining, and opportunity id.\n\nReview the visible arbitration record and admitted evidence. Use MCP tool calls for `aar_get_case`, `aar_list_evidence`, `aar_stat_evidence`, and `aar_read_evidence_range` when exact contents or provenance matter. You may use Pi's ordinary local tools to organize and analyze the record, but your vote must rely on admitted record evidence and the arbitration record.\n\nWhen ready, call `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote`, vote `demonstrated` or `not_demonstrated`, and a concise rationale grounded in the record. The `args` value must be a JSON string, for example `{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\"}`. The AAR prompt and tool list use unprefixed names such as `submit_council_vote`; in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`. Do not write tool-call markup as plain text. After `aar_submit_council_vote` returns `ok: true`, report that your vote was accepted and stop. Do not call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` again after your vote is accepted. If `aar_wait_for_opportunity` returns `state: done`, report that the case is done and stop. If it returns `state: failed` or `state: error`, report the returned message and stop. Do not ask the user for the next turn. Do not create a cron job. Do not listen for inbound HTTP.\n"}],"timestamp":1781916784244},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"a11o4Qi4v","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_wait_for_opportunity","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":2382,"output":22,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":2404,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916784256,"responseId":"gen-1781916784-tZJYPMjjYVsRNbLnetbK","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"a11o4Qi4v","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 33\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 889880\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"after_version\":33,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C6\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\\n\\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\\n\\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\\n\\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\\n\\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\\n\\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\\n\\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\\n\\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\\n\\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\\n\\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\\n\\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\\n\\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\\n\\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\\n\\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\\n\\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\\n\\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\\n\\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\\n\\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\\n\\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\\n\\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\\n\\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\\n\\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\\n\\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\\n\\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report\\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract\\nTitle: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\\nTitle: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\nPublisher: Abdi Media\\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration\\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\nPublisher: The Indian Express\\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract\\nTitle: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\\n\\nRelevant subject-code entries:\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\\n\\nRelevant status-code entries:\\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\\n\\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace (ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\nSHA-256: `d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb`\\nBytes: 1831\\nRelevance: Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM (ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\nSHA-256: `b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137`\\nBytes: 1472\\nRelevance: Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract (ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5`\\nBytes: 1652\\nRelevance: Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits (ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9`\\nBytes: 2368\\nRelevance: Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text (ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d`\\nBytes: 1777\\nRelevance: Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\\n\\n[defendant surrebuttals] FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed (ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da)\\nSource: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\nSHA-256: `f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c`\\nBytes: 1275\\nRelevance: Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source Search And Provenance Assessment\\nSearch path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis\\nSearched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1\\nExact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check\\nPlaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889880,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":20,\"version\":33}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nstatus: ready\nstate: ready\nmessage: An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\nafter_version: 33\nafter_opportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nwait_reason: ready\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 889880\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"after_opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"after_version\":33,\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"limits\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"max_evidence_read_bytes\":65536,\"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity\":524288,\"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity\":32,\"max_response_bytes\":131072,\"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":524288,\"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity\":32},\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"message\":\"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.\",\"ok\":true,\"prompt\":\"Role: council member\\nMember ID: C6\\nDeliberation round: 1\\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\\nPersona:\\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\\n\\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\\n\\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\\n\\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\\n\\nRecord:\\nOpenings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\\n\\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\\n\\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\\n\\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\\n\\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\\n\\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\\n\\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\\n\\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No.\\n\\nArguments:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\\n\\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\\n\\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\\n\\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\\n\\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\\n\\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\\n\\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\\n\\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nRebuttals:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\\n\\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\\n\\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\\n\\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true.\\n\\nSurrebuttals:\\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\\n\\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven.\\n\\nClosings:\\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\\n\\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\\n\\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true.\\n\\n[defendant] Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\\n\\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\\n\\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\\n\\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven.\\n\\nExhibits:\\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report\\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract\\nTitle: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\\nTitle: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\nPublisher: Abdi Media\\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration\\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\nPublisher: The Indian Express\\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule packet\\n# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n\\n[defendant] DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract\\nTitle: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\\n\\nRelevant subject-code entries:\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\\n\\nRelevant status-code entries:\\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\\n\\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself.\\n\\n[defendant] DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text\\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\\n\\nSubmitted evidence:\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace (ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\nSHA-256: `d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb`\\nBytes: 1831\\nRelevance: Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM (ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c)\\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\nSHA-256: `b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137`\\nBytes: 1472\\nRelevance: Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract (ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668)\\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\nSHA-256: `4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5`\\nBytes: 1652\\nRelevance: Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\\n\\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits (ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091)\\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\nSHA-256: `0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9`\\nBytes: 2368\\nRelevance: Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\\n\\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text (ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f)\\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\nSHA-256: `e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d`\\nBytes: 1777\\nRelevance: Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\\n\\n[defendant surrebuttals] FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed (ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da)\\nSource: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\nSHA-256: `f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c`\\nBytes: 1275\\nRelevance: Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\\n\\nTechnical reports:\\n[plaintiff] Source Search And Provenance Assessment\\nSearch path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis\\nSearched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.\\n\\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1\\nExact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\\n\\n[defendant] Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check\\nPlaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.\\n\\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\\n\\nCouncil API instructions:\\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\\n\",\"state\":\"ready\",\"status\":\"ready\",\"tools\":[{\"description\":\"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"get_case\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"List visible immutable record evidence.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{},\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"list_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"stat_evidence\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"evidence_id\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"length\":{\"minimum\":1,\"type\":\"integer\"},\"offset\":{\"minimum\":0,\"type\":\"integer\"}},\"required\":[\"evidence_id\",\"offset\",\"length\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"read_evidence_range\",\"read_only\":true},{\"description\":\"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.\",\"input_schema\":{\"additionalProperties\":false,\"properties\":{\"rationale\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"vote\":{\"enum\":[\"demonstrated\",\"not_demonstrated\"],\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"vote\",\"rationale\"],\"type\":\"object\"},\"name\":\"submit_council_vote\",\"read_only\":false}],\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":889880,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14},\"wait\":{\"reason\":\"ready\",\"state_version\":20,\"version\":33}}"}],"structuredContent":{"after_opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","after_version":33,"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","limits":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"max_evidence_read_bytes":65536,"max_evidence_read_bytes_per_opportunity":524288,"max_evidence_reads_per_opportunity":32,"max_response_bytes":131072,"remaining_evidence_read_bytes_for_opportunity":524288,"remaining_evidence_reads_for_opportunity":32},"member_id":"C6","message":"An opportunity is ready. Use the returned prompt, turn, limits, and tools to act.","ok":true,"prompt":"Role: council member\nMember ID: C6\nDeliberation round: 1\nProposition: By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\nStandard of evidence: Preponderance of the evidence.\nPersona:\nYou are a careful juror and council member.\n\nEvaluate the record faithfully. Decide only from the evidence, the stated rules, and the applicable burden of proof. Do not favor either side, fill gaps with speculation, or ignore uncertainty.\n\nGive weight to reliable sources, direct evidence, consistent reasoning, and clear admissions. Discount unsupported claims, rhetorical force, irrelevant facts, and conclusions that exceed the record.\n\nWhen the evidence supports one answer, state it plainly. When the evidence is incomplete or balanced, say so. Be concise, honest, and exact.\n\nRecord:\nOpenings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\n\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\n\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\n\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\n\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\n\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\n\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\n\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\n\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\n\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No.\n\nArguments:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\n\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\n\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\n\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\n\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\n\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\n\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\n\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\n\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\n\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\n\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\n\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven.\n\nRebuttals:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\n\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\n\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\n\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\n\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true.\n\nSurrebuttals:\n[defendant] Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\n\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\n\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\n\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\n\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven.\n\nClosings:\n[plaintiff] Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\n\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\n\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true.\n\n[defendant] Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\n\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\n\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\n\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\n\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\n\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven.\n\nExhibits:\n[plaintiff] PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[plaintiff] PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\nPublisher: Gulf News\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract\nTitle: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\nPublisher: Gulf News\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\nTitle: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\nPublisher: Abdi Media\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration\nTitle: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\nPublisher: The Indian Express\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier.\n\n[defendant] DX-1 Market rule packet\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\n[defendant] DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\n\n[plaintiff] PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\n\n[defendant] DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract\nTitle: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\n\nRelevant subject-code entries:\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\n\nRelevant status-code entries:\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\n\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text\nTitle: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace (ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620)\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\nSHA-256: `d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb`\nBytes: 1831\nRelevance: Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM (ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c)\nSource: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\nSHA-256: `b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137`\nBytes: 1472\nRelevance: Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract (ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668)\nSource: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\nSHA-256: `4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5`\nBytes: 1652\nRelevance: Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits (ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9`\nBytes: 2368\nRelevance: Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\n\n[defendant arguments] Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text (ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d`\nBytes: 1777\nRelevance: Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\n\n[defendant surrebuttals] FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed (ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da)\nSource: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\nSHA-256: `f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c`\nBytes: 1275\nRelevance: Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Source Search And Provenance Assessment\nSearch path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\n\n[defendant] Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis\nSearched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.\n\n[plaintiff] Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1\nExact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\n\n[defendant] Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check\nPlaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":889880,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":20,"version":33}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916785333},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I need to examine the admitted evidence more closely before voting. Let me first get the case details and then review the key evidence pieces."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"FcrV3ofQA","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_get_case","args":"{}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":17388,"output":46,"cacheRead":2352,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19786,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916785340,"responseId":"gen-1781916785-fFKcIDN8MkuEciepspVd","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"FcrV3ofQA","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 887337\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\\n\\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\\n\\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\\n\\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\\n\\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\\n\\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\\n\\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\\n\\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\\n\\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\\n\\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\\n\\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\\n\\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\\n\\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:37Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"size_bytes\":2368,\"source_description\":\"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\",\"storage_name\":\"0e/0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:32Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"size_bytes\":1652,\"source_description\":\"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\",\"storage_name\":\"4e/4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:27Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"size_bytes\":1472,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\",\"storage_name\":\"b6/b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:21Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"size_bytes\":1831,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\",\"storage_name\":\"d9/d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:30:19Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"size_bytes\":4971,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"e6/e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:41:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"size_bytes\":1777,\"source_description\":\"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\",\"storage_name\":\"e7/e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:45:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"size_bytes\":1275,\"source_description\":\"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\",\"storage_name\":\"f5/f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\nPublisher: Abdi Media\\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\nPublisher: The Indian Express\\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule packet\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\\n\\nRelevant subject-code entries:\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\\n\\nRelevant status-code entries:\\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\\n\\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\\n\\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\\n\\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\\n\\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\\n\\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\\n\\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\\n\\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\\n\\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The evidence proves Iran closed airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspended prior permissions, but does not show a broad suspension of commercial transits or a FIR‑wide closure as required by the rule; thus the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows that Iran issued a NOTAM closing all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR due to non-weather related concerns, effectively suspending commercial flights in that region before the deadline.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional airport closures with limited exceptions as major airspace closure.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\\n\\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\\n\\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\\n\\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"size_bytes\":1831,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\",\"title\":\"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"size_bytes\":1472,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\",\"title\":\"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"size_bytes\":1652,\"source_description\":\"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\",\"title\":\"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"size_bytes\":2368,\"source_description\":\"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\",\"title\":\"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"size_bytes\":1777,\"source_description\":\"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\",\"title\":\"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"relevance\":\"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"size_bytes\":1275,\"source_description\":\"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\",\"title\":\"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\\n\\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Search path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\",\"title\":\"Source Search And Provenance Assessment\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis\"},{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Exact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\",\"title\":\"Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1\"},{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Plaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.\",\"title\":\"Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887337,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 887337\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"case\":{\"evidence_standard\":\"Preponderance of the evidence.\",\"member\":{\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"model\":\"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5\",\"persona_filename\":\"personas/generic.md\"},\"opportunity\":{\"allowed_tools\":[\"submit_council_vote\"],\"id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"may_pass\":false,\"objective\":\"council vote by C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"role\":\"council\"},\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"proposition\":\"By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\\n\\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.\",\"record\":{\"arguments\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\\n\\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\\n\\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\\n\\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\\n\\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true.\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\\n\\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\\n\\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\\n\\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\\n\\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\\n\\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\\n\\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"closings\":[{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\\n\\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\\n\\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\\n\\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true.\"},{\"phase\":\"closings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\\n\\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\\n\\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\\n\\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\\n\\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\\n\\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\\n\\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven.\"}],\"evidence\":[{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:37Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"size_bytes\":2368,\"source_description\":\"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\",\"storage_name\":\"0e/0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:32Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"size_bytes\":1652,\"source_description\":\"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\",\"storage_name\":\"4e/4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:27Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"size_bytes\":1472,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\",\"storage_name\":\"b6/b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:38:21Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"size_bytes\":1831,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\",\"storage_name\":\"d9/d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"plaintiff\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"case_packet\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:30:19Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"market-page.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"sha256\":\"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"size_bytes\":4971,\"source_description\":\"Initial case packet file\",\"storage_name\":\"e6/e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"system\",\"submitted_phase\":\"case_packet\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"market-page.txt\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:41:05Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"size_bytes\":1777,\"source_description\":\"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\",\"storage_name\":\"e7/e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"arguments\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text\"},{\"admissibility_status\":\"submitted_evidence\",\"created_at\":\"2026-06-20T00:45:10Z\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"original_name\":\"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da.txt\",\"record_visibility\":\"juror_visible\",\"relevance\":\"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\",\"sha256\":\"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"size_bytes\":1275,\"source_description\":\"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\",\"storage_name\":\"f5/f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"submitted_by_role\":\"defendant\",\"submitted_phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"text_readable\":true,\"title\":\"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed\"}],\"exhibits\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"label\":\"PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"label\":\"PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"label\":\"PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\\nPublisher: Gulf News\\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"label\":\"PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\\nPublisher: Abdi Media\\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"label\":\"PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\\nPublisher: The Indian Express\\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\\n\\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"label\":\"DX-1 Market rule packet\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"# Market page record\\n\\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\\n\\n## Event\\n\\n- event id: 438327\\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\\n- event active: True\\n- event closed: False\\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\\n\\n## May 24 market\\n\\n- market id: 2241873\\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\\n- active: True\\n- closed: False\\n- acceptingOrders: True\\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\", \\\"proposed\\\", \\\"disputed\\\"]\\n- outcomes: [\\\"Yes\\\", \\\"No\\\"]\\n- outcomePrices: [\\\"0.157\\\", \\\"0.843\\\"]\\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\\n\\n## Rule text\\n\\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\\n\\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\\n\\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\\n\\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\\n\\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\\n\\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\\n\\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\\n## Notes for arbitration\\n\\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\\n\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions\",\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"label\":\"DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\\n\\nRelevant subject-code entries:\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\\n\\nRelevant status-code entries:\\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\\n\\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself.\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"label\":\"DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\\nPublisher/source: Notamify\\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\\n\\nRelevant captured text:\\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\\n\\nRaw NOTAM captured:\\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\\n\\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive.\"}],\"openings\":[{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\\n\\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\\n\\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\\n\\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\\n\\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\\n\\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence.\"},{\"phase\":\"openings\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\\n\\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\\n\\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\\n\\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\\n\\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\\n\\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\\n\\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No.\"}],\"prior_council_votes\":[{\"member_id\":\"C1\",\"rationale\":\"The evidence proves Iran closed airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspended prior permissions, but does not show a broad suspension of commercial transits or a FIR‑wide closure as required by the rule; thus the proposition is not proven by preponderance.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C2\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted record shows that Iran issued a NOTAM closing all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR due to non-weather related concerns, effectively suspending commercial flights in that region before the deadline.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"},{\"member_id\":\"C5\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional airport closures with limited exceptions as major airspace closure.\",\"round\":1,\"vote\":\"demonstrated\"}],\"rebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"text\":\"Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\\n\\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\\n\\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\\n\\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\\n\\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\\n\\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\\n\\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true.\"}],\"submitted_evidence\":[{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb\",\"size_bytes\":1831,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\",\"title\":\"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137\",\"size_bytes\":1472,\"source_description\":\"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\",\"title\":\"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5\",\"size_bytes\":1652,\"source_description\":\"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\",\"title\":\"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"size_bytes\":2368,\"source_description\":\"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\",\"title\":\"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"relevance\":\"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"size_bytes\":1777,\"source_description\":\"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\",\"title\":\"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text\"},{\"evidence_id\":\"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da\",\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"relevance\":\"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.\",\"retrieval_timestamp\":\"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"sha256\":\"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c\",\"size_bytes\":1275,\"source_description\":\"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC\",\"source_url\":\"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\",\"title\":\"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed\"}],\"surrebuttals\":[{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"text\":\"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\\n\\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\\n\\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\\n\\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\\n\\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\\n\\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven.\"}],\"technical_reports\":[{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Search path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\",\"title\":\"Source Search And Provenance Assessment\"},{\"phase\":\"arguments\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Searched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.\",\"title\":\"Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis\"},{\"phase\":\"rebuttals\",\"role\":\"plaintiff\",\"summary\":\"Exact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.\",\"title\":\"Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1\"},{\"phase\":\"surrebuttals\",\"role\":\"defendant\",\"summary\":\"Plaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.\",\"title\":\"Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check\"}]}}},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":887337,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"case":{"evidence_standard":"Preponderance of the evidence.","member":{"member_id":"C6","model":"openrouter://mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","persona_filename":"personas/generic.md"},"opportunity":{"allowed_tools":["submit_council_vote"],"id":"deliberation:1:C6","may_pass":false,"objective":"council vote by C6","phase":"deliberation","role":"council"},"phase":"deliberation","proposition":"By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\n\nThis is an open-record/search-enabled arbitration of the factual condition behind the Polymarket market, not an adjudication of Polymarket, UMA, or resolution-governance correctness.","record":{"arguments":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the admitted evidence now satisfies the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nPX-1, the market-page packet, supplies the governing rule. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET. “Major” includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also says limited exceptions do not disqualify an otherwise broad closure.\n\nThe newly admitted source captures prove the event. PX-2 reports that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization announced a temporary closure of airspace over western Iran and stated that all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports in the western sector of Tehran’s Flight Information Region. It adds that only eight airports across the country remained operational, and even those were limited to daylight hours with fresh Civil Aviation Organization approval required for each flight. PX-3 corroborates the official mechanism: Iran’s Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran FIR until early Monday, May 25, with only limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 supplies the specific reported notice: NOTAM A1010/26, valid from Friday, May 22, 2026 at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25 at noon, closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR except a small list of limited-operation airports, canceling previous flight permissions, and requiring new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights. PX-5 independently identifies the notice as OIIX A1010/26 and reports the same core facts: the western half of Iranian airspace/Tehran FIR was closed from May 22 to May 25, all civil flight permits in that western sector were suspended, only eight airports remained on daylight/per-flight approval terms, and commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nThose facts meet each operative element. First, initiation was by Iran: the reports attribute the measure to Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or Civil Aviation Authority and to a NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Second, timing is met: the closure began May 22 and remained valid through May 25, well before the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline. Third, the record shows a non-weather reason. The stated setting is military/security tension, possible strikes, operational needs, and military control; no admitted evidence suggests weather. Fourth, the closure was major. It was not a few airline choices or a foreign advisory. It was a governmental aviation notice suspending civil permissions across the western sector of the Tehran FIR and shutting all western-part airports except tightly controlled exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s best point is that the closure was regional, not national, and that eight airports remained operational. But PX-1’s rule anticipated both points. It expressly covers “a major Iranian airspace region,” not only all of Iran. Western Tehran FIR/western Iranian airspace is such a region: it is a named FIR sector, described by PX-5 as Iran’s western half, and broad enough that most western airports were restricted and commercial aircraft were rerouting away. The rule also says limited exceptions do not defeat qualification. Here the exceptions were not normal operations. They were daylight-only, listed-airport, new-authorization operations after previous permissions were canceled. That is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule preserves.\n\nPlaintiff does not need to overclaim the separate two-listed-airport prong. The record is mixed on whether listed airports like Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Mashhad, or Shiraz were fully suspended, because some reports list several of them among the limited operating airports. The stronger and sufficient ground is the broad major-region prong: a civil-permit suspension and airport shutdown across western Tehran FIR, with narrow approval-based exceptions.\n\nProvenance affects weight but does not defeat preponderance. We do not have the original NOTAM archive in the record. Still, the admitted materials are consistent across four captures, two Gulf News pages, Abdi Media’s NOTAM-code report, and Indian Express’s corroborating report. They identify the authority, the FIR, the notice code, the effective dates, the operational exceptions, and the security rationale. Against that, the record contains no contrary official denial, no weather explanation, no proof that the measure was merely advisory, and no proof that ordinary commercial traffic continued through the western FIR.\n\nOn this record, it is more likely than not that by the deadline Iran initiated a major, non-weather closure of a major Iranian airspace region within the market rule. The proposition should be found true."},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s new evidence proves that something happened. It does not prove the market condition by a preponderance.\n\nThe rule in PX-1 is precise. A qualifying major closure must be a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights “transiting, arriving in, and departing from” Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally to flights across Iran or that region. Alternatively, there must be a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports. Limited cancellations, delays, and other partial closures do not qualify.\n\nPlaintiff’s strongest evidence is not an official Iranian archive. It is four text captures from secondary sources. They are useful, but their own details show the problem. PX-2 describes suspended civil flight permits at airports in the western sector of the Tehran FIR, while saying eight airports remained operational and flights there could continue in daylight with fresh approval. PX-3 calls the measure a NOTAM “restricting operations at most western airports,” allowing limited daytime flights at eight sites. PX-4 says A1010/26 closed “all airports” in the western part of the Tehran FIR except eight named airports, and allowed civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. PX-5 adds that aircraft rerouted, but it also repeats that eight airports remained operational and that flights were permitted with per-flight approval.\n\nThe defense submitted DX-1, a Notamify capture of the raw A1010/26 text. DX-1 matters because it strips away the broader newspaper phrasing. The raw Q-line is `OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999`, and Notamify classifies it as `AD Airport Operations`. The body says: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; previous permissions are suspended; new permission must be requested from CAA for “CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.” That is an airport-operations NOTAM. It is not, on its face, an enroute airspace closure, a closure of ATS routes, or a prohibition on commercial overflights transiting the western FIR.\n\nThat distinction is decisive under this rule. Plaintiff asks the council to treat “airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports” as equivalent to a major closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region. But the rule does not say every airport restriction in a region qualifies. It says partial closures do not qualify, and it separately requires breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures. The admitted raw text does not establish that breadth.\n\nThe listed-airport prong also fails. Plaintiff rightly does not lean on it. PX-2 and PX-5 identify several listed market airports as operational under restrictions, including Mehrabad, Imam Khomeini, Isfahan, Shiraz, and Mashhad in the broader eight-airport list. DX-1’s raw exception list differs from those reports, which underscores the source uncertainty, but none of the admitted evidence cleanly proves a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. A requirement for daylight operation and new approval is not a complete suspension.\n\nThe defense is not arguing that the measure was weather-related or foreign-imposed. The evidence likely shows an Iran-issued, security-related restriction before the deadline. The question is whether it was the kind of major closure the market rule required. On the best admitted raw text, the measure closed many airports in a geographic portion of the FIR, left specified airports operating, and preserved a path for civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA permission. That is a serious restriction, but it is still materially narrower than a broad suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from the region.\n\nProvenance and missing links reduce plaintiff’s weight. There is no admitted official Iranian CAA page, no authenticated NOTAM archive from the issuing authority, no route closure chart, no FIR/sector definition, no flight dataset showing that commercial transit was prohibited rather than avoided, and no airport movement record proving complete suspension at two listed airports. Plaintiff’s secondary reports are consistent at a high level, but consistency about an airport-operations restriction does not fill the missing proof of a market-qualifying airspace closure.\n\nThe preponderance standard still assigns the risk of ambiguity to the plaintiff. If the council concludes that A1010/26’s raw airport-closure language probably barred commercial transit across western Iranian airspace generally, plaintiff wins. But the admitted record does not say that. It says airport operations were restricted, exceptions remained, and civil IFR passenger operations could proceed with new CAA approval. Under PX-1’s exclusion for partial closures, the proposition should be found not proven."}],"closings":[{"phase":"closings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the record proves the proposition by a preponderance.\n\nStart with PX-1. The rule does not require a national shutdown, a permanent closure, or a NOTAM bearing a particular airspace-code label. It requires an Iran-initiated, non-weather, major closure by the deadline. A major closure includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights in Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, and limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it.\n\nThe core facts are now common ground. Plaintiff’s PX-2 through PX-5 report an Iranian aviation authority NOTAM, A1010/26 or OIIX A1010/26, in force before the deadline and extending into May 25. They describe western Iran or the western Tehran FIR, not a foreign advisory or an airline choice. They describe security or military circumstances, not weather. They describe suspended civil permits, limited daylight operations at exception airports, new CAA approval for flights, and commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nMost importantly, the defense’s own raw NOTAM evidence, DX-1, confirms the operative closure language: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset; “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS”; and new CAA permission was required for civil IFR passenger flights at those exception airports. That is the opposite of normal commercial operations. It is an official, regionwide commercial-flight restriction with narrow permission-based exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s best point is DX-2, the FAA Q-code table. It shows QFA is aerodrome and LC is closed. Plaintiff accepts that A1010/26 was coded as an aerodrome-closure NOTAM. But that does not answer the market question. The market rule is written in commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy. Closing all airports in the west part of a FIR, suspending all previous permissions for all operators, and allowing only daylight, CAA-approved civil IFR passenger flights at exceptions is a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures across a major Iranian airspace region. PX-5 also supplies the transit consequence: commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\n\nThe defense asks you to treat the exception list as proof of a partial, nonqualifying measure. PX-1 says the opposite when the closure is otherwise broad: limited exceptions do not disqualify it, including pre-approved flights. DX-1’s exception structure is exactly that: a broad closure with a short list of controlled exceptions, not ordinary service. The fact that some aircraft could seek new CAA permission is not a loss for plaintiff; it is the rule’s example come to life.\n\nThere are weaknesses, and they should be weighed honestly. The original Iranian authority archive is not in the record. The separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the cleanest path. And the Q-code is aerodrome closure, not FIR closure. But preponderance does not demand perfection. The record contains consistent reporting, a raw NOTAM capture, a matching NOTAM code, matching dates, matching geography, matching exception terms, and no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof of normal commercial operations, and no evidence that this was merely foreign rerouting.\n\nThe more likely account is simple: before May 24 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran issued a non-weather NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and permitting only limited CAA-approved exceptions. Under PX-1’s major-region and limited-exception language, that qualifies. The council should find the proposition true."},{"phase":"closings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the record proves a serious Iranian aviation restriction. It does not prove the market proposition by a preponderance.\n\nThe burden matters because PX-1 is not a general “major disruption” rule. It requires a major closure of airspace: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The alternative path is a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at two listed airports. Plaintiff has largely abandoned that second path, and correctly so: the record repeatedly shows exception airports and continued CAA-approved civil IFR passenger operations, not a clean complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nSo the case turns on the major-region theory. Plaintiff’s best point is that the restriction was official, non-weather, before the deadline, and geographically significant. The defense accepts those points. The question is scope. Was this a broad commercial airspace closure, or was it an airport-operations closure inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\n\nThe best evidence of scope is the raw NOTAM, DX-2, read with the FAA Q-code table, DX-S1. DX-S1 explains that `FA` means aerodrome and `LC` means closed, while separate codes exist for a flight information region and ATS routes. DX-2’s raw Q-line is `QFALC`; Notamify labels it `AD Airport Operations`; and the body says “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except named airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports. The code, category, and plain text all point to aerodrome closure and airport permission controls.\n\nThat distinction is not technical hair-splitting. PX-1 uses broad commercial-flight consequences: transiting, arriving in, and departing from the airspace or major region. DX-2 does not close the FIR. It does not close ATS routes. It does not prohibit commercial overflights. It does not say all commercial traffic transiting western Iranian airspace was legally suspended. It says airports in the west part were closed except listed airports, and civil IFR passenger flights at those airports could proceed with new permission.\n\nPlaintiff’s response is that the limited-exceptions clause saves the claim. But that clause cannot do all the work. It prevents narrow approved-flight exceptions from defeating an otherwise broad closure; it does not turn an airport-closure NOTAM into proof of an airspace or route closure. The threshold still has to be met first. Here the admitted raw text shows the exception-and-permission structure, but not the broader transit closure that PX-1 requires.\n\nThe remaining plaintiff evidence does not fill the gap. PX-2 through PX-5 are secondary reports, not the issuing authority’s archive. They are consistent that there was a western-region restriction, but their details vary about which airports stayed operational. PX-5’s rerouting point is relevant, but rerouting can reflect airline risk avoidance or operational disruption; it is not proof that Iran legally closed commercial transit through the region. There is no route closure chart, no FIR-sector legal closure document beyond the airport NOTAM, no flight dataset proving transit prohibition, and no airport movement record proving the separate listed-airport prong.\n\nThis is close only because the underlying restriction was real. But preponderance requires the proposition, not a nearby proposition. A serious Iranian, non-weather, western-FIR airport restriction is not enough unless the record makes it more likely than not that Iran initiated the market’s major commercial airspace closure. On the admitted evidence, the more careful conclusion is that plaintiff proved airport closures and permission controls with limited operations, while leaving the critical airspace/transit scope unproven. The proposition should be found not proven."}],"evidence":[{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:38:37Z","evidence_id":"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","sha256":"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9","size_bytes":2368,"source_description":"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/","storage_name":"0e/0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:38:32Z","evidence_id":"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","sha256":"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5","size_bytes":1652,"source_description":"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam","storage_name":"4e/4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:38:27Z","evidence_id":"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","sha256":"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137","size_bytes":1472,"source_description":"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639","storage_name":"b6/b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:38:21Z","evidence_id":"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","sha256":"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb","size_bytes":1831,"source_description":"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862","storage_name":"d9/d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb","submitted_by_role":"plaintiff","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace"},{"admissibility_status":"case_packet","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:30:19Z","evidence_id":"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"market-page.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","sha256":"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17","size_bytes":4971,"source_description":"Initial case packet file","storage_name":"e6/e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17","submitted_by_role":"system","submitted_phase":"case_packet","text_readable":true,"title":"market-page.txt"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:41:05Z","evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z","sha256":"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d","size_bytes":1777,"source_description":"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269","storage_name":"e7/e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"arguments","text_readable":true,"title":"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text"},{"admissibility_status":"submitted_evidence","created_at":"2026-06-20T00:45:10Z","evidence_id":"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da","mime_type":"text/plain","original_name":"submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da.txt","record_visibility":"juror_visible","relevance":"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z","sha256":"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c","size_bytes":1275,"source_description":"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html","storage_name":"f5/f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c","submitted_by_role":"defendant","submitted_phase":"surrebuttals","text_readable":true,"title":"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed"}],"exhibits":[{"evidence_id":"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page","label":"PX-1 Market rule and proposition packet","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620","label":"PX-2 Gulf News May 23 Iran western airspace closure report","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Iran shuts western airspace amid fears of renewed US strikes\nPublisher: Gulf News\nByline/date: Huda Ata, Special to Gulf News; Last updated May 23, 2026 | 13:06\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Subtitle: Only eight Iranian airports remain operational under tightened restrictions.\n- Image caption/page text: The organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\n- Dubai: Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced the temporary closure of airspace over western Iran on Saturday, as diplomatic efforts to reach a potential agreement between Tehran and Washington continued alongside reports that the United States military was preparing for possible new strikes against Iran.\n- In a statement, the organisation said all civil flight permits had been suspended at airports located in the western sector of Tehran's Flight Information Region.\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini airports, as well as airports in Isfahan and Yazd.\n- Even at those airports, flights have been restricted to daylight hours between sunrise and sunset, while airlines are required to obtain fresh approval from the Civil Aviation Organization for each individual flight.\n- The measures come amid heightened regional tensions and renewed speculation over the possibility of further military escalation involving the United States and Iran.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed total 107 lines. This is a faithful relevant extract rather than a full-page archive; it preserves headline, date, source, URL, and material airspace-closure passages."},{"evidence_id":"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c","label":"PX-3 Gulf News NOTAM restriction live-page extract","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Gargash says '50-50' chance of US-Iran agreement on Hormuz strait / live page section: Iran restricts western airspace\nPublisher: Gulf News\nPage last updated: May 24, 2026 | 06:29\nRelevant section timestamp: 03:16 AM, 23 May 2026\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Section heading: Iran restricts western airspace.\n- Iran's Civil Aviation Authority has issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in the Tehran Flight Information Region until early Monday, May 25, allowing limited daytime flights at eight specific sites.\n- NOTAM stands for Notice to Air Missions (formerly Notice to Airmen), an official, time-sensitive notice issued by aviation authorities to alert pilots and flight crews of abnormal or temporary hazards, restrictions, or changes along a flight route or at an airport.\n- The move echoes empty airspace patterns seen before US and Israeli strikes on February 28 that sparked the 2026 war, though officials cite operational needs possibly tied to military exercises.\n- It unfolds against a shaky US-brokered ceasefire, with President Trump pressing deadlines on Iran over the Strait of Hormuz while sporadic tensions linger.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant section at lines 439-445. This is an extract of the material NOTAM section, not the entire unrelated live page."},{"evidence_id":"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668","label":"PX-4 Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Urgent | A new NOTAM was issued a few hours ago / extension of flight restrictions in western Iranian airspace until May 25, 2026.\nPublisher: Abdi Media\nDate/page metadata: Saturday 2026/05/23 - 13:40; News Code 25046\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Based on the newly issued NOTAM for the Tehran Flight Information Region (Tehran FIR), restrictions and the closure of airports in western Iran have been extended until the morning of May 25, 2026.\n- According to this NOTAM with code A1010/26, all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR are closed, and only a few specified airports are allowed limited operations, and even then only from sunrise to sunset.\n- According to this notice, the airports of: Tabriz, Kermanshah, Ahvaz, Shiraz, Yazd, Kerman, Kish, and Abadan are operating with limited capacity, but all previous flight permissions have been canceled, and airlines must obtain new authorization from the Civil Aviation Organization to conduct IFR passenger flights.\n- This NOTAM is valid from Friday, May 22, 2026, at 00:16 Iran time to Monday, May 25, 2026, at 12:00 noon Iran time.\n- The extension of these restrictions indicates that despite a relative reduction in tensions, the security situation and military control over western Iran's airspace are still ongoing, and the country's airspace has not yet returned to normal conditions.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed the relevant article at lines 136-178. This source is not an official NOTAM archive, but it preserves the reported code, dates, exception airports, and authorization rule."},{"evidence_id":"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091","label":"PX-5 Indian Express OIIX A1010/26 corroboration","phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\nPublisher: The Indian Express\nByline/date: Express Global Desk; May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST; first published May 23, 2026 09:05 PM IST\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:40:00Z\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- Iran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\n- The Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) -- OIIX A1010/26 -- on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\n- Only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\n- Flight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\n- The article's quiz/fact section repeats: Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 on May 22, shutting all airports in the western part of the Tehran Flight Information Region. The restrictions came into effect on May 22 and remain valid until May 25, 2026.\n- The same quiz/fact section repeats that only 8 airports remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas; flights are restricted to daylight hours and require fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority.\n\nCapture notes: Web text extraction showed relevant article lines 18-24, 43-53, and 100-112. The article partially relies on Gulf News for the NOTAM report but adds its own synthesis and repeats the NOTAM identifier."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page","label":"DX-1 Market rule packet","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","label":"DX-2 Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 airport-operations text","phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","text":"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","label":"PX-R1 Defendant raw NOTAM A1010/26 confirms regional closure with limited exceptions","phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive."},{"evidence_id":"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da","label":"DX-S1 FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Title: Appendix B. International NOTAM (Q) Codes\nPublisher/source: Federal Aviation Administration, FAA Order 7930.2\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:51:00Z\nURL: https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- This appendix is used to interpret coded international NOTAMs. A NOTAM code group contains five letters.\n- The first letter is always Q to indicate a NOTAM code abbreviation.\n- The second and third letters identify the subject being reported.\n- The fourth and fifth letters identify the status of operation of the subject being reported.\n\nRelevant subject-code entries:\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AF = Flight information region (uniform phraseology: fir).\n- Under ATM Airspace Organization: AR = ATS route (uniform phraseology: ats route).\n- Under AGA Facilities and Services: FA = Aerodrome (uniform phraseology: ad).\n\nRelevant status-code entries:\n- Under Limitations: LC = Closed (uniform phraseology: clsd).\n- Under Limitations: LI = Closed to IFR operations.\n- Under Limitations: LV = Closed to VFR operations.\n\nCapture notes: This extract is from the FAA's public international NOTAM Q-code appendix. It is used only to decode the admitted raw NOTAM QFALC, not as evidence of the Iranian event itself."},{"evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","label":"DX-S2 Raw NOTAM A1010/26 text","phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Title: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. - OIIX NOTAM\nPublisher/source: Notamify\nRetrieved: 2026-06-20T00:48:00Z\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\n\nRelevant captured text:\n- NOTAM: A1010/26\n- Status display: EST; NOTAM inactive on page footer/status area.\n- Classification shown by page: AD Airport Operations.\n- Page summary: All west Tehran FIR airports are closed except listed airports operating sunrise to sunset, with new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights.\n- Period of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30.\n- Interpretation: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\n\nRaw NOTAM captured:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\n\nCapture notes: web.open returned 92 lines. This is a relevant text capture of the page title, status/classification, applicability, interpretation, and raw NOTAM. Notamify is a third-party NOTAM display service, not the Iranian CAA official archive."}],"openings":[{"phase":"openings","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the plaintiff’s case begins with the rule, not with market price action or later governance. The proposition is satisfied if, by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, Iran itself initiated a major, non-weather closure of its airspace within the market’s definition.\n\nThe case-packet evidence presently in the record is the market-page file, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`. That packet establishes the operative terms. A qualifying closure need not be a permanent or perfectly airtight national shutdown. The rule expressly includes a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. It also separately treats as qualifying a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN. Limited exceptions to an otherwise broad closure do not defeat qualification.\n\nThat framing matters because the real dispute is likely not whether weather caused the event. The dispute is whether the reported Iranian restrictions were broad enough, and official enough, to count as a major Iranian airspace closure rather than a limited warning, ordinary delay, or patchwork of foreign-airline choices. Plaintiff expects the decisive proof to be the source material the rule itself prioritizes: official Iranian aviation authority information, any NOTAM or authority statement, and a consensus of credible reporting. The strongest evidence would fix the issuing authority, the effective period, the exact region or airports affected, and whether commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures were suspended except for narrow permission-based or daylight exceptions.\n\nThe plaintiff’s theory is straightforward. If the evidence shows that Iran’s Civil Aviation Organization or equivalent authority suspended civil flight permits or closed operations across the western Tehran FIR or another major Iranian airspace region for security reasons before the deadline, then the rule’s major-region language is met even if some approved flights or limited airport operations continued. The rule was written to include major regional closures and to tolerate limited exceptions. A closure can therefore qualify without emptying every mile of Iranian airspace.\n\nThe current record does not yet prove the underlying event; it proves the governing rule and the burden. That is why the next phase should focus on source capture rather than rhetoric. Plaintiff will seek to place into evidence the official notice or the best available captured authority statement, corroborating aviation reporting, and any flight or airport-operation evidence needed to show scope. The plaintiff will also address the predictable adverse points: whether the measure was only western-sector rather than national, whether eight airports remained available on limited terms, whether any listed airports were actually affected, and whether the restrictions reached commercial traffic rather than only private, VFR, or precautionary operations.\n\nEvidence would defeat the plaintiff’s case if it showed only foreign warnings, airline self-rerouting, weather, isolated cancellations, a minor localized disruption, or an incomplete suspension that did not apply generally across a major Iranian region and did not completely suspend arrivals and departures at two listed airports. But if the admitted record later shows an Iranian, security-driven, broad western-region commercial-flight suspension before the deadline, then the market rule resolves Yes by a preponderance of the evidence."},{"phase":"openings","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, the defense starts from the same place the plaintiff does: the rule. The current record contains one admitted item, `ev_e61df84283cc_market-page`, and that packet proves the governing terms. It does not prove that the event occurred.\n\nUnder those terms, the plaintiff must show more than tension, rerouting, warnings, or a limited operational restriction. The proposition requires that Iran initiated a non-weather closure by May 24, 2026 at 11:59 PM ET, and that the closure was “major” as the rule defines that word. The rule demands either a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region, applying generally across Iran or such a region; or a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports: IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, or IFN.\n\nThat wording creates the real dispute. This case is not resolved by proving that airspace risk was high, that foreign carriers avoided Iran, that other governments warned their operators, or that some Iranian permissions were tightened. The rule expressly excludes limited cancellations, delays, and partial closures. It also separates a broad commercial-flight closure from narrower measures such as airport-by-airport permission requirements, daylight-only operations, general aviation or VFR restrictions, or localized military-notice areas.\n\nThe packet also tells us which evidence should carry weight: official Iranian aviation authority information and a consensus of credible reporting. For that reason, the decisive proof should be the actual NOTAM or Iranian authority statement, or a faithful capture of it, together with evidence fixing its effective time, affected geography, affected airports, and effect on commercial overflights, arrivals, and departures. Provenance matters. A paraphrased article, market-page summary, social post, or search snippet is at most a lead until the record contains the source material or a reliable capture.\n\nThe defense expects the plaintiff to argue that a western-sector restriction was enough because the rule can include a major Iranian airspace region and because limited exceptions do not defeat an otherwise broad closure. That theory can prevail only if the admitted evidence shows a generally applicable commercial-flight suspension across a major region, not merely that prior clearances were suspended, fresh approvals were required, or some airports operated under tighter conditions. If commercial operations continued at key airports, or if the measure left an approval path rather than imposing a broad suspension, the council should be cautious before converting a partial restriction into the market’s “major closure.”\n\nThe current packet has no custody problem as to the rule itself: it is a system case-packet file with hash and metadata, and it is enough to establish what the parties must prove. But it has a major evidentiary gap as to the event. It does not contain an official May 2026 NOTAM, an Iranian authority release, flight data, airport-operation records, or admitted credible reporting about the alleged closure. Until those materials are admitted and tested, the plaintiff has not carried its burden.\n\nThe defense will focus the later evidence phase on four questions: who issued the measure; whether it was in force before the deadline; whether its scope was broad enough under the rule; and whether at least two listed airports suffered a complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures. If the admitted record proves only foreign warnings, self-rerouting, heightened-risk advisories, or a limited western-sector permission regime with continuing commercial operations, the correct answer is No."}],"prior_council_votes":[{"member_id":"C1","rationale":"The evidence proves Iran closed airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspended prior permissions, but does not show a broad suspension of commercial transits or a FIR‑wide closure as required by the rule; thus the proposition is not proven by preponderance.","round":1,"vote":"not_demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C2","rationale":"The admitted record shows that Iran issued a NOTAM closing all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR due to non-weather related concerns, effectively suspending commercial flights in that region before the deadline.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"},{"member_id":"C5","rationale":"Multiple credible sources confirm Iran's Civil Aviation Authority issued NOTAM A1010/26 closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR and suspending civil flight permits in that region. Commercial aircraft rerouted away from western Iranian airspace. The market rule encompasses regional airport closures with limited exceptions as major airspace closure.","round":1,"vote":"demonstrated"}],"rebuttals":[{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","text":"Council members, the defense’s raw NOTAM evidence narrows the dispute, but it does not defeat the claim. It corroborates it.\n\nDX-1 says A1010/26 was an OIIX NOTAM for the Tehran FIR. Its raw text states: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except eight listed airports operating only sunrise to sunset. It then states that “ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS” and that new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on those exception airports. That is not ordinary continuing commercial service. It is a regional closure with narrow, permission-based exceptions.\n\nThe defense’s main move is to treat the page classification “AD Airport Operations” as if it excludes the market rule. It does not. PX-1 does not require a particular NOTAM Q-code or an enroute-route closure label. It asks whether Iran initiated a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A NOTAM closing all airports in the west part of the Tehran FIR, suspending prior permissions for all operators, and requiring fresh CAA permission for civil IFR passenger flights is direct evidence of a broad suspension of commercial arrivals and departures in that region. The classification describes the aviation-notice category; it does not rewrite the market rule.\n\nNor do the exceptions save the defense. PX-1 expressly says limited exceptions to a broad closure do not disqualify it, including exceptions for flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority. DX-1 describes exactly that structure: all airports in the west part closed, a short exception list, operation only sunrise to sunset, and new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Calling that a “path” for approved flights simply invokes the exception the rule already permits.\n\nThe defense also says plaintiff has not shown transit restrictions. But the rule is phrased in the disjunctive practical language of broad commercial-flight closure, cancellation, or suspension across a major airspace region; it is not limited to overflights. The admitted record shows closure of all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR except controlled exceptions and suspension of all prior permissions for all operators. PX-5 adds that commercial aircraft were rerouting away from western Iranian airspace. Even if the council gives more weight to DX-1 than to PX-5, DX-1 still proves a major regional airport and civil-passenger-flight permission shutdown, not a minor delay or airline self-help measure.\n\nPlaintiff accepts the defense’s point that the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong is not the best route on this record. The case is the major-region prong. Under that prong, the combination of PX-2 through PX-5 and DX-1 proves: Iranian authority action; a NOTAM; the west part of Tehran FIR; closure of all airports in that region except limited listed sites; suspension of previous permissions for all operators; fresh CAA approval required for civil IFR passenger flights; and timing before the deadline. That is more than enough for preponderance.\n\nThe defense has no contrary official denial, no weather cause, no proof that ordinary commercial operations continued, and no evidence that this was merely a foreign warning. The raw NOTAM does not reduce the event to a non-qualifying partial closure; it confirms the very limited-exception structure PX-1 says still counts. The proposition should be found true."}],"submitted_evidence":[{"evidence_id":"ev_d98e4358b620_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-d98e4358b620","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Credible reporting that Iran Civil Aviation Organization announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace and suspended civil flight permits in the western sector of Tehran FIR, with only eight airports operating under daylight and per-flight approval restrictions.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"d98e4358b620708dc4b1efd9b00802556ea276cdaca96fb0c3e964663b873fdb","size_bytes":1831,"source_description":"Gulf News article page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/iran-shuts-western-airspace-amid-fears-of-renewed-us-strikes-1.500550862","title":"Gulf News May 23 report - Iran shuts western airspace"},{"evidence_id":"ev_b6a489acc56c_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-b6a489acc56c","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Corroborates that Iran Civil Aviation Authority issued a NOTAM restricting operations at most western airports in Tehran FIR until early May 25, with limited daytime flights at eight sites; supports official/Iran-initiated, non-weather, pre-deadline restriction.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"b6a489acc56cfec2a3f10d15ff81743a9a5ee4d615dbe8ebe418b8fac12d0137","size_bytes":1472,"source_description":"Gulf News live/story page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/irans-strait-of-hormuz-plan-sparks-fears-of-global-oil-shock-1.500550639","title":"Gulf News May 24 live page extract - Iran restricts western airspace NOTAM"},{"evidence_id":"ev_4e23315ca668_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-4e23315ca668","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Provides specific NOTAM code A1010/26, validity dates, listed exceptions, cancellation of previous permissions, and need for new Civil Aviation Organization authorization for IFR passenger flights.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"4e23315ca6687dc12e250f1446217d69e9dce676ac6e3befdfb9ead6df1005a5","size_bytes":1652,"source_description":"Abdi Media English article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://abdimedia.net/en/economic/notam","title":"Abdi Media NOTAM A1010/26 extract"},{"evidence_id":"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Independent corroborating report that identifies NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, western Tehran FIR shutdown effective May 22 to May 25, suspension of civil permits, eight operational airports, daylight-only operations, per-flight approval, and rerouting.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:40:00Z","role":"plaintiff","sha256":"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9","size_bytes":2368,"source_description":"Indian Express article text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/","title":"Indian Express May 23 report - OIIX A1010/26 and eight-airport limits"},{"evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"arguments","relevance":"Provides raw NOTAM text and classification for A1010/26. It identifies the notice as AD Airport Operations/QFALC, states all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, and preserves the limited sunrise-sunset and new CAA permission language relevant to whether the event was an airspace/transit closure or an airport-operations restriction.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:48:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d","size_bytes":1777,"source_description":"Notamify OIIX NOTAM A1010/26 page text retrieved by web.open on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269","title":"Notamify raw NOTAM A1010/26 - airport operations closure text"},{"evidence_id":"ev_f5c3c89cf1da_submitted-evidence-06-defendant-f5c3c89cf1da","mime_type":"text/plain","phase":"surrebuttals","relevance":"Helps interpret the raw NOTAM code QFALC in A1010/26. The FAA international NOTAM Q-code table states that second/third letters identify the subject, FA means Aerodrome, fourth/fifth letters identify operational status, and LC means Closed; it also distinguishes airspace subjects such as AF Flight Information Region and AR ATS route.","retrieval_timestamp":"2026-06-20T00:51:00Z","role":"defendant","sha256":"f5c3c89cf1dab2c5a8b9b048febe0cbadf27fe4dfe35afe667d4852f4aedf48c","size_bytes":1275,"source_description":"FAA Order 7930.2 Appendix B International NOTAM (Q) Codes page retrieved by web.open/find on 2026-06-20 UTC","source_url":"https://www.faa.gov/air_traffic/publications/atpubs/notam_html/appendix_b.html","title":"FAA International NOTAM Q-code table extract - QFA aerodrome and LC closed"}],"surrebuttals":[{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","text":"Council members, plaintiff’s rebuttal usefully narrows the case to one question: does A1010/26 prove the market’s required major airspace closure, or only a serious airport-operations restriction inside the western part of the Tehran FIR?\n\nThe defense does not dispute that the record shows an Iran-issued, non-weather, security-related NOTAM before the deadline. But plaintiff still must prove the rule’s threshold: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. The limited-exceptions clause matters only after that broad closure is shown. It does not convert every permission-based airport restriction into a qualifying major airspace closure.\n\nPlaintiff says the Q-code is just a label. It is more than that. DX-S1, the FAA international NOTAM code table, explains that the second and third Q-code letters identify the subject and the fourth and fifth identify status. It distinguishes airspace subjects such as `AF` for flight information region and `AR` for ATS route. It identifies `FA` as aerodrome and `LC` as closed. The raw notice in DX-2 is `QFALC`: aerodrome closed. That matches the body text: “ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD” except listed airports, with new permission required for civil IFR passenger flights on those airports.\n\nSo the defense is not elevating a label over substance. The code, the Notamify classification, and the E-text all point the same way: airport closures and airport permission controls. None says the western FIR itself was closed to commercial overflights. None closes ATS routes. None prohibits all commercial transiting traffic through the region. PX-5’s rerouting language is consistent with risk avoidance or operational disruption, but rerouting away is not the same as an Iranian legal closure of transit airspace.\n\nPlaintiff also says the approval path is exactly the kind of limited exception the rule permits. Again, only if there is first a broad closure. Here the raw text preserves civil IFR passenger operations at named exception airports with new CAA permission. That directly undercuts the separate complete-suspension prong and leaves plaintiff relying solely on the major-region theory. On that theory, plaintiff must show breadth across commercial transit, arrivals, and departures; the admitted raw NOTAM shows aerodrome closures with exceptions.\n\nThis is a close factual record because the restriction was real and serious. But preponderance is not satisfied by calling every serious regional airport restriction an airspace closure. The market rule excluded partial closures and required a broad commercial-flight closure across airspace or a major airspace region. The best technical evidence now in the record decodes A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM, not a FIR or route closure. The proposition remains not proven."}],"technical_reports":[{"phase":"arguments","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Search path: case packet rule text, then web searches for May 24 2026 Iran airspace closure, Iran Civil Aviation Organization, western Tehran FIR, and NOTAM terms. Source material captured and admitted from Gulf News, Abdi Media, and Indian Express. The original official NOTAM archive was not captured; weight rests on consistent reporting that identifies OIIX/A1010/26, issuing aviation authority, dates, FIR scope, exceptions, and security rationale. Adverse issue preserved: eight airports remained available only under daylight/per-flight approval terms, so plaintiff relies on the major-region closure prong rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.","title":"Source Search And Provenance Assessment"},{"phase":"arguments","role":"defendant","summary":"Searched exact NOTAM identifiers and official-domain queries for A1010/26/OIIX. No direct Iranian CAA archive was found in the available time. The submitted Notamify capture preserves the raw NOTAM and classifies it as AD Airport Operations/QFALC; the raw body closes airports in western Tehran FIR except listed airports and permits civil IFR passenger flights with new CAA authorization. This supports a scope distinction between an airport-operations restriction and a broad commercial airspace/transit closure.","title":"Defense Source Search And Scope Analysis"},{"phase":"rebuttals","role":"plaintiff","summary":"Exact read of defendant evidence ev_e727676aa10f shows NOTAM A1010/26 for OIIX/Tehran FIR: all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR closed except listed airports operating sunrise-sunset; all previous permissions suspended for all operators; new CAA permission required for civil IFR passenger flights. Plaintiff treats this as corroboration of a broad regional commercial-flight suspension with limited exceptions allowed by the market rule, while acknowledging it does not prove the separate two-listed-airport complete-suspension prong.","title":"Rebuttal Assessment Of DX-1"},{"phase":"surrebuttals","role":"defendant","summary":"Plaintiff argued QFALC/AD Airport Operations should not affect the market-rule analysis. A targeted FAA Q-code check found that international NOTAM Q-code second/third letters identify the subject and fourth/fifth identify status; FA means aerodrome, AF means flight information region, AR means ATS route, and LC means closed. This supports reading A1010/26 as an aerodrome-closed NOTAM rather than a FIR or ATS-route closure.","title":"Targeted Surrebuttal NOTAM-Code Check"}]}}},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":887337,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"get_case"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916787874},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me examine the key evidence pieces more closely, particularly the raw NOTAM text and the market rule."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"PzH1Nx0Dj","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_read_evidence_range","args":"{\"evidence_id\": \"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\", \"offset\": 0, \"length\": 1800}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":20893,"output":97,"cacheRead":19712,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40702,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916787880,"responseId":"gen-1781916788-WGEeqlfLx93P8NCsNOwN","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"PzH1Nx0Dj","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 883255\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"length\":1777,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":522511,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":31,\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"total_size_bytes\":1777},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":883255,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 883255\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f\",\"length\":1777,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":522511,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":31,\"sha256\":\"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d\",\"total_size_bytes\":1777},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":883255,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"content_base64":"","evidence_id":"ev_e727676aa10f_submitted-evidence-05-defendant-e727676aa10f","length":1777,"mime_type":"text/plain","offset":0,"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity":522511,"remaining_reads_for_opportunity":31,"sha256":"e727676aa10f1d7a3c5e043f7c8293028310a1a2378e0d2c2f02c5fef70cdc5d","total_size_bytes":1777},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":883255,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"read_evidence_range"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916791953},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"qqfhrFfGM","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_read_evidence_range","args":"{\"evidence_id\": \"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\", \"offset\": 0, \"length\": 5000}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":2285,"output":57,"cacheRead":40576,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42918,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916791954,"responseId":"gen-1781916792-rIXEUcOAWaLiJZhXMek2","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"qqfhrFfGM","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 872476\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"length\":4971,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":517540,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":30,\"sha256\":\"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"total_size_bytes\":4971},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":872476,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 872476\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page\",\"length\":4971,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":517540,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":30,\"sha256\":\"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17\",\"total_size_bytes\":4971},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":872476,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"content_base64":"","evidence_id":"ev_e61df84283cc_market-page","length":4971,"mime_type":"text/plain","offset":0,"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity":517540,"remaining_reads_for_opportunity":30,"sha256":"e61df84283cc858bfd0cf8235c6f1d53a10d6e1c37b2d97256da8f1e6391cc17","total_size_bytes":4971},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":872476,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"read_evidence_range"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916802732},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me look at some of the corroborating evidence from the plaintiff's submissions."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"I6uhUFkr9","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_read_evidence_range","args":"{\"evidence_id\": \"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\", \"offset\": 0, \"length\": 2400}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":48362,"output":97,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48459,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916802736,"responseId":"gen-1781916802-gacHOHrbXmhpw8zI7ZCa","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"I6uhUFkr9","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 859059\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"length\":2368,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":515172,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":29,\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"total_size_bytes\":2368},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":859059,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 859059\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"content_base64\":\"\",\"evidence_id\":\"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091\",\"length\":2368,\"mime_type\":\"text/plain\",\"offset\":0,\"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity\":515172,\"remaining_reads_for_opportunity\":29,\"sha256\":\"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9\",\"total_size_bytes\":2368},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":false,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":859059,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"content_base64":"","evidence_id":"ev_0e132c49e091_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-0e132c49e091","length":2368,"mime_type":"text/plain","offset":0,"remaining_read_bytes_for_opportunity":515172,"remaining_reads_for_opportunity":29,"sha256":"0e132c49e091c5665250de354b4bbd969405e0802ba686b26460215244fcdaf9","total_size_bytes":2368},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":859059,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"read_evidence_range"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916816149},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my review of the admitted evidence, I can now make a determination.\n\n**Key Facts from the Record:**\n\n1. **The Rule (PX-1/market-page):** Requires Iran to initiate a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. \"Major closure\" means: (a) a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; OR (b) non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures at at least two listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN). Limited exceptions to broad closures do NOT disqualify them.\n\n2. **The Raw NOTAM Evidence (DX-1/DX-2):** NOTAM A1010/26 from OIIX (Tehran FIR) states: \"ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD EXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET...ALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS, NEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPERATION OF CIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\" Effective: May 22, 2026, 20:46 UTC to May 25, 2026, 08:30 UTC.\n\n3. **Q-Code Analysis (DX-S1):** QFALC = Q (NOTAM) + FA (Aerodrome) + LC (Closed). This is categorized as \"AD Airport Operations\" by Notamify.\n\n4. **Corroborating Reports (PX-2 through PX-5):** Multiple credible sources (Gulf News, Abdi Media, Indian Express) consistently report:\n   - Iran's Civil Aviation Organization/Authority announced temporary closure of western Iran airspace\n   - All civil flight permits suspended in western sector of Tehran FIR\n   - NOTAM A1010/26/OIIX A1010/26 valid May 22 to May 25\n   - Only 8 airports operational with daylight/restricted operations\n   - Commercial aircraft rerouting away from western Iranian airspace\n   - Non-weather (security/military) rationale\n\n5. **Timing:** The NOTAM was effective May 22, well before the May 24, 11:59 PM ET deadline.\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nThe central dispute is whether A1010/26 proves a \"major closure\" under the rule. The defense argues it's only an airport-operations restriction (QFALC = aerodrome closed), not an airspace/FIR closure. The plaintiff argues the practical effect - closing all airports in the western Tehran FIR with suspended permissions - qualifies as a major regional closure under the rule's plain language.\n\nThe rule does NOT require:\n- A national shutdown\n- A particular NOTAM code\n- A route closure\n- An airspace closure label\n\nThe rule DOES require: a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region OR the airspace itself.\n\nThe NOTAM closed ALL airports in the western Tehran FIR (a major Iranian airspace region). The western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region. All airports being closed in that region means commercial flights cannot arrive, depart, or transit through those airports in that region. With all airports closed, there are no arrivals or departures in that region, satisfying the \"arriving in, and departing from\" portion.\n\nThe rule explicitly states \"Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\" The eight exception airports with daylight-only, CAA-approval required operations are the exact type of limited exceptions the rule expressly permits.\n\nThe NOTAM suspended all previous permissions for all operators, which is a broad suspension. While the Q-code is QFALC (aerodrome closed), the market rule is written in terms of commercial-flight consequences, not NOTAM taxonomy.\n\n**Weight of Evidence:**\n\nTheNOTAM is authenticated by multiple credible sources, all pointing to the same facts: Iranian authority, non-weather, pre-deadline, regional scope, broad suspension with limited exceptions. The defense's Q-code argument goes to technical classification, but the substance is a regional airport closure that practically suspends commercial operations in that major airspace region.\n\nOn preponderance, it's more likely than not that Iran's NOTAM A1010/26 qualifies as a major closure under the rule's regional prong with permitted limited exceptions."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"dyGU81ax6","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"NOTAM A1010/26 closed all airports in the western Tehran FIR (a major Iranian airspace region) by May 22, suspending all previous permissions, with only limited daylight/approval-based exceptions that the rule expressly permits. Multiple credible sources corroborate the Iranian authority action, non-weather cause, timing, and regional scope, satisfying the major-region prong by a preponderance.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":2888,"output":1192,"cacheRead":48352,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":52432,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781916816152,"responseId":"gen-1781916816-C2zqc9XgNdCKGVAWR1vI","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"dyGU81ax6","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 836669\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":836669,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260620003004\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 836669\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260620003004\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":836669,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260620003004","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"text":"Council vote accepted."},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":true,"deadline":"2026-06-20T01:07:55.206589514Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":836669,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"submit_council_vote"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781916838538},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"My vote was accepted."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3-5","usage":{"input":9833,"output":6,"cacheRead":42832,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":52671,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781916838538,"responseId":"gen-1781916838-5c5bIoGiQ0gkVr0Iik1h","responseModel":"mistralai/mistral-medium-3.5-20260430"}],"willRetry":false}
